moAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fgender"],"summaryLong":"Every day around the world, 137 women are killed by an intimate partner or a family member. One programme in India seeks to end violence against women – by focusing on teenaged boys.","summaryShort":"Is this the key to ending gender-based violence?","tag":["tag\u002Fgender"],"creationDateTime":"2019-11-12T01:30:18.932846Z","entity":"article","guid":"a212912f-a726-4fc9-8756-8456085dfcc7","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191111-gender-based-violence-prevention-project-in-india","modifiedDateTime":"2019-11-12T10:30:01.05269Z","project":"future","slug":"20191111-gender-based-violence-prevention-project-in-india","cacheLastUpdated":1587443048832},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis","_id":"5e98209f8ec3f2455a11d1e6","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fleila-mcneill"],"bodyIntro":"She fled the Nazis, only to face a new challenge: being accepted in academia.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen 46-year-old Hilda Geiringer arrived in New York with her daughter Magda, she must have felt relieved. The year was 1939. And Geiringer, as well as a talented mathematician, was a Jewish woman from Vienna.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor six years, she&rsquo;d been seeking an escape from the Nazi threat in Europe. In that time, she&rsquo;d fled to Turkey, been stranded in Lisbon and narrowly escaped internment at a Nazi camp. Her arrival in the US should have opened a new, and far better, chapter.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut it brought other challenges.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe first woman to teach applied mathematics at a German university, Geiringer was known as an innovative thinker who applied her mathematical insight to other sciences. But in the US, she struggled for decades to regain her status in the field.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis wasn&rsquo;t because of Geiringer&rsquo;s talent, or lack thereof: she was part of an early vanguard in 20th-Century applied mathematics at a time when the field was trying to find institutional legitimacy and independence from pure mathematics. With crucial contributions to mathematical theories of plasticity and to probability genetics, Geiringer helped advance the field of applied mathematics, laying fundamental groundwork which many parts of science and engineering rely upon today.\u003Cem\u003E \u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20171009-the-female-code-breakers-who-were-left-out-of-history-books\"\u003EThe female code-breakers who were left out of history\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190606-the-maths-problem-that-modern-life-depends-on\"\u003EThe maths problem that could bring the world to a halt\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die\"\u003EThe sexist myths that won't die\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut Geiringer&rsquo;s work was more than her livelihood. It was her calling. &ldquo;I must work scientifically,&rdquo; she wrote in a 1953 letter to the president of Wheaton College in Massachusetts. &ldquo;It is perhaps the deepest need in my life.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhether she would be allowed to fulfil that need &ndash; and under what circumstances &ndash; was, after how she would manage to flee the Nazis, one of the biggest questions of her life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"I must work scientifically. It is perhaps the deepest need in my life – Hilda Geiringer","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifferent beginnings\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer was born in Vienna in 1893. In a time when women were largely expected to pursue marriage over scholarship, Geiringer&rsquo;s parents took a different view and encouraged their daughter&rsquo;s education. They sent her to advanced secondary school, then paid for her study of mathematics and physics at the University of Vienna.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile there, Geiringer studied under some of the most prestigious European mathematicians of the early 20th Century, including \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.britannica.com\u002Fbiography\u002FErnst-Mach\"\u003EErnst Mach\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (think \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.grc.nasa.gov\u002Fwww\u002Fk-12\u002Fairplane\u002Fmach.html\"\u003EMach speed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E) and her doctoral mentor \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk\u002FBiographies\u002FWirtinger.html\"\u003EWilhelm Wirtinger\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (known for \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fself.gutenberg.org\u002Farticles\u002Fwirtinger's_derivatives\"\u003EWirtinger derivatives\u003C\u002Fa\u003E). She received her doctoral degree in mathematics in 1917; the next year her dissertation, in which she tackled advanced trigonometry and developed a generalised theory for a Fourier series in two variables, was published in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007%2FBF01700482\"\u003EMonatshefte f&uuml;r Mathematik und Physik\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E (Mathematics and Physics Monthly)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDespite having nurtured Geiringer&rsquo;s burgeoning skill and love for mathematics, Vienna held few opportunities for a female Jewish mathematician, so Wirtinger secured a position for her in Berlin as assistant editor of the mathematics journal \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.emis.de\u002FMATH\u002FJFM\u002F\"\u003EJarhbuch &uuml;ber die Fortschritte der Mathematik\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E (Almanac for the Progress of Mathematics)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E. In 1921 she became assistant to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk\u002FBiographies\u002FMises.html\"\u003ERichard von Mises\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, the director of the recently established Institute for Applied Mathematics at the University of Berlin (now Humboldt University of Berlin). And six years later, at the age of 34, Geiringer became more than an assistant: she became the first female lecturer (&ldquo;Privadozent&rdquo;) at the university. She was the first woman in Germany to hold such a role in applied mathematics.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07sms5j"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt was shortly after, at age 37, that Geiringer made one of her most significant contributions to applied mathematics. Although she was trained as a pure mathematician, Geiringer had become increasingly focused on applied mathematics under von Mises &ndash; specifically in the areas of statistics, probability, and plasticity. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EPlastic deformation occurs when forces cause an object to be permanently distorted. Von Mises was looking for ways to simplify differential equations that determine plastic deformation in metals.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer found a way to combine two conditions into a single equation, greatly simplifying and speeding up the process of calculating deformation. This is known now as the Geiringer equations. With her equations, Geiringer became a co-developer of the slip-line theory, a set of simplification techniques that analyses the conditions in metal deformation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Even today, slip-line theory plays a central role in science and engineering","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEven today, slip-line theory plays a central role in science and engineering. In safety engineering for bridges, for instance, application of this theory ensures that metals don&rsquo;t strain beyond their deformation point, preventing bends and breaks. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn 1933, Geiringer&rsquo;s talent was recognised further when she was nominated for an assistant professor position.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut the Nazi party took over German politics the same year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefugee status\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe party enacted a flurry of legislation to disenfranchise Jews. One was the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fghdi.ghi-dc.org\u002Fsub_document.cfm?document_id=1520\"\u003ELaw for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service Act\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, which barred &ldquo;non-Aryans&rdquo; from holding positions in government institutions. Along with hundreds of other Jewish intellectuals, Geiringer lost her university position.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAlong with her daughter Magda, born from Geiringer&rsquo;s marriage to a fellow mathematician which had ended in divorce, she needed to leave. After a brief stay in Brussels, she and Magda moved to Istanbul.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAt the time, Turkey&rsquo;s president Mustafa Kemal Ataturk was instituting nationwide reforms to modernise the country and higher education post-independence from the Ottoman Empire. This included welcoming nearly 200 German scholars, among them von Mises and Geiringer. Von Mises was appointed chair of mathematics at the newly founded Istanbul University while Geiringer became professor with a five-year contract.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07sms8f"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer thrived in Istanbul. She pursued multiple avenues of research, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS0315086012000377\"\u003Epublishing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E 18 articles in English and even a calculus textbook in Turkish.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EShe also conducted innovative research in probability theory and Mendelian genetics by configuring recursive equations to study the distribution of genotypes and blood types.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut this work, too, came crashing down. Turkish professors began to replace the Jewish refugees at the university, and Geiringer was one of those replaced. Her contract wasn&rsquo;t renewed, and von Mises wouldn&rsquo;t stay at the university without her. Making their situation more precarious, Ataturk died in 1938. Along with him went many of the protections and reforms that Jewish refugees enjoyed. Feeling it was no longer safe, Geiringer and von Mises left.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThey set their sights on the US, where scientists like Albert Einstein and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.britannica.com\u002Fbiography\u002FOswald-Veblen\"\u003EOswald Veblen\u003C\u002Fa\u003E were attempting to place their colleagues. But immigrating to America, with its strict annual quotas, wasn&rsquo;t easy, especially in 1939. As \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcamd.northeastern.edu\u002Ffaculty\u002Flaurel-leff\u002F\"\u003ELaurel Leff\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, creator of the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.northeastern.edu\u002Frefugeescholars\u002Fabout\"\u003ERediscovering the Refugee Scholars of the Nazi Era project\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, explains, by the time Geiringer was trying to immigrate, the quota for that year had already been met.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The reason that 1939 was the year that the quota was filled was because that was after Kristallnacht,&rdquo; says Leff. Kristallnacht, also called the Night of Broken Glass, was a clear indication to the world that the Nazi party was intensifying its violence against Jewish people. For two days and nights, Nazis swept through Germany, burning more than 1,000 synagogues, vandalising Jewish homes and businesses and killing nearly 100 Jews.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07smsyh"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EUS immigration law had a small non-quota loophole &ndash; a provision called Section 4-D. &ldquo;This is the one that is relevant when you&rsquo;re talking about scientists and scholars,&rdquo; Leff says. &ldquo;It was basically for people [who] were getting jobs at American universities; they could immigrate on a non-quota visa.&rdquo; For the entirety of the war, Leff says, only 900 people were granted non-quota visas.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENon-quota visas posed unique challenges for women, who often were unable to find professorial positions &ndash; usually the reserve of men &ndash; whether in their home country or the US.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer was no different. Von Mises secured a position at Harvard University and, thus, a visa.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut without a home or job, Geiringer was quite literally cut adrift. While she and Magda were en route to the Mediterranean from London, World War Two officially began, stranding them in Lisbon as their German passports were denied for entry back to England. Without permission to stay in Lisbon, Geiringer and Magda were faced with deportation to Germany and internment in a Nazi camp. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer&rsquo;s correspondence to von Mises, and her mentor&rsquo;s journals from the time, reflect a tangible sense of desperation. On the day he learned of Geiringer&rsquo;s abandonment in Lisbon, von Mises wrote in his journal (reproduced in the book \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpress.princeton.edu\u002Ftitles\u002F8955.html\"\u003EMathematicians Fleeing From Nazi Germany\u003C\u002Fa\u003E) that he &ldquo;immediately decided to undertake steps&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETogether with Einstein and Veblen, he reached out to women&rsquo;s colleges Bryn Mawr and Smith College, hoping to secure Geiringer a job &ndash; and with it a visa. Geiringer even suggested that they marry to hurry the immigration process. On days when von Mises didn&rsquo;t receive any word from Geiringer, he vented his panic, at one point writing, &ldquo;worn out and almost desperate&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07smtvs"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut Bryn Mawr, a women&rsquo;s college in Pennsylvania, came through. Even though the position they offered was unpaid, Geiringer took it, and she and Magda received their visas. After six years of uncertainty, they could settle. Von Mises and Geiringer even married soon after, in 1943.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe imminent threat of the Holocaust had passed for Geiringer, but her troubles weren&rsquo;t over.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMath demand\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhen Geiringer was looking for positions during World War Two, applied mathematics was in demand in the United States. &ldquo;The growth of applied mathematics in the US has to do with war-related research,&rdquo; says Alma Steingart, historian of applied mathematics at Columbia University in New York. &ldquo;A lot of it comes from the fact that this is war preparation and there&rsquo;s mobilisation on many fronts.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven after the war, the field grew. &ldquo;Funding starts coming into applied mathematics. And this recognition by the American mathematical community itself, that they need to start making sure that applied mathematics is well-developed in the US&rdquo; grows, she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut despite demand and Geiringer&rsquo;s qualifications, her gender disqualified her for many jobs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Mathematics is one of the worst fields in terms of women’s participation – Alma Steingart","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Mathematics is one of the worst fields in terms of women&rsquo;s participation,&rdquo; Steingart says. Even Brown University, which Steingart says was one of the two main sites for applied mathematics and where Geiringer developed a series of acclaimed lectures on the geometrical foundation of mechanics, did not offer her employment.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne response to her inquiries for employment at Tufts College near Boston left little room for speculation about why she couldn&rsquo;t find a job: &ldquo;...it is not merely prejudice against women, yet it is partly that, for we do not want to bring in more if we can get men&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAfter five years at Bryn Mawr and searching for a university position, Geiringer became head of the mathematics department at Wheaton College, another women&rsquo;s college in Norton, Massachusetts. &ldquo;The places where women were most likely to get hired would be women&rsquo;s colleges as opposed to universities,&rdquo; Leff says. &ldquo;[Hilda] was able to get a job at a women&rsquo;s college, because women&rsquo;s colleges would hire women.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07smv2g"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWomen&rsquo;s colleges provided essential opportunities for women as both professors and students. But, as Leff points out, &ldquo;women&rsquo;s colleges were colleges&rdquo;, so they didn&rsquo;t support the same type of sophisticated research that Geiringer had been doing in universities. Any research she did would be outside of her college duties and typically unpaid.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGeiringer never found in a US university a position equal to what she had in Germany and Turkey.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAfter accepting her post at Wheaton, Geiringer wrote to von Mises, &ldquo;I hope there will be better conditions for the next generations of women. In the meantime, one has to go on as well as possible.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd Geiringer did go on. She stayed at Wheaton, which granted her an honorary doctorate in mathematics, until her retirement in 1959, that same year, she was elected a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. She still did research when she found the time, but her most significant project post-immigration was compiling, editing, and publishing von Mises&rsquo; unfinished book in two editions after his death in 1953: Probably, Statistics, and Truth in 1964 and Mathematical Theory of Probability and Statistics in 1957.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven if Geiringer didn&rsquo;t get exactly what she wanted, she never gave up on chasing that deepest need in her life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMissed Genius\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAsk people to imagine a scientist, and many of us will picture the same thing &ndash; a heterosexual white male. Historically, a number of challenges have made it much more difficult for those who don&rsquo;t fit that stereotype to enter fields like science, math or engineering.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere are, however, many individuals from diverse backgrounds who have shaped our understanding of life and the Universe, but whose stories have gone untold &ndash; until now. With our new BBC Future column, we are celebrating the &ldquo;missed geniuses&rdquo; who made the world what it is today.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPortrait of Hilda Geiringer by Emmanuel Lafont.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or\u003Cstrong\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Worklife, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis-16"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fmissed-genius"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-11-01T01:01:01Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The woman who reshaped maths","headlineShort":"The woman who reshaped maths","image":["p07smvpy"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e9821448ec3f2455a175f56"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fgender"],"summaryLong":"She fled the Nazis, only to face a new challenge: being accepted in academia.","summaryShort":"She fled the Nazis – but her challenges didn’t end","tag":["tag\u002Fmathematics","tag\u002Fgender"],"creationDateTime":"2019-11-01T09:58:53.045092Z","entity":"article","guid":"c68795b2-7dd0-4b69-aeb3-77beba9df1e5","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis","modifiedDateTime":"2019-11-01T13:58:37.110845Z","project":"future","slug":"20191031-hilda-geiringer-mathematician-who-fled-the-nazis","cacheLastUpdated":1587443048832},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die","_id":"5e98209d8ec3f2455a11c87b","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fdavid-robson"],"bodyIntro":"Gina Rippon has spent her career trying to debunk the idea that men and women’s brains are different – yet she believes the “gender bombardment” we are subjected to is greater than ever. Why?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen I meet the cognitive neuroscientist Gina Rippon, she tells me one anecdote that helps demonstrate just how early children can be exposed to gender stereotypes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt was the birth of her second daughter, on 11 June 1986 &ndash; the night that Gary Lineker scored a hat trick against Poland in the men&rsquo;s Football World Cup. There were nine babies born in the ward that day, Rippon recalls. Eight of them were called Gary.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Subtle cues about &ldquo;manly&rdquo; and &ldquo;ladylike&rdquo; behaviours, from the moment of birth, mould our behaviours and abilities","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EShe remembers chatting to one of the other mums when they heard a loud din approaching. It was a nurse bringing their two screaming babies. The nurse handed her neighbour a &ldquo;blue-wrapped Gary&rdquo; with approval &ndash; he had &ldquo;a cracking pair of lungs&rdquo;. Rippon&rsquo;s own daughter (making exactly the same sound) was passed over with an audible tutting. &ldquo;She&rsquo;s the noisiest of the lot &ndash; not very ladylike,&rdquo; the nurse told her.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;And so, at 10 minutes old, my tiny daughter had a very early experience of how gendered our world is,&rdquo; Rippon says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERippon has spent decades questioning ideas that the brains of men and women are somehow fundamentally different &ndash; work that she compellingly presents in her new book, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.penguin.co.uk\u002Fbooks\u002F111\u002F1114075\u002Fthe-gendered-brain\u002F9781847924759.html\"\u003EThe Gendered Brain\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The title is slightly misleading, since her argument hinges on the fact that it&rsquo;s \u003Cem\u003Enot\u003C\u002Fem\u003E the human brain that is inherently &ldquo;gendered&rdquo;, but the world in which we are raised. Subtle cues about &ldquo;manly&rdquo; and &ldquo;ladylike&rdquo; behaviours, from the moment of birth, mould our behaviours and abilities, which other scientists have then read as inherent, innate differences.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190913-why-some-children-become-merciless-bullies\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EWhy children become bullies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190211-the-dark-side-of-believing-in-true-love\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe dark side of believing in true love\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190424-the-hidden-trauma-of-childbirth\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe effect of childbirth no-one talks about\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERippon&rsquo;s writing bristles with frustration that this argument still needs to be stated in 2019. She describes many of the theories about gender differences as &ldquo;whack-a-mole&rdquo; myths that keep on arising, in another guise, no matter how often they are debunked.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We've been looking at this whole issue of whether male brains are different from female brains for about 200 years,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;And every now and then there's a new breakthrough in science or technology, which allows us to revisit this question, and make us realise that some of the past certainties are clearly wrong. And you think that, as a scientist, you might have addressed them and put them right, and people will move on and not use those terms or conclusions anymore. But the next time you look at the popular press you find that the old myth has returned.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Video","iFrameType":"","videoImageAlign":"centre","videoUrn":["p07l2bx3"],"id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou can see Gina Rippon discussing these myths in the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Freel\u002Fvideo\u002Fp07l2bx3\u002Fare-male-and-female-brains-different-\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EBBC Reel video\u003C\u002Fa\u003E above.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the oldest claims centres on the fact that women have smaller brains, which was considered evidence for intellectual inferiority. While it&rsquo;s true that, on average, women&rsquo;s brains are smaller, by about 10%, there are several problems with this assumption.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;First of all, if you just thought it was a &lsquo;size matters&rsquo; issue, then sperm whales and elephants have got bigger brains than men, and they're not renowned for being that much brighter,&rdquo; says Rippon. Then there&rsquo;s the fact that, despite the average difference in size, the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencemag.org\u002Fnews\u002F2017\u002F04\u002Fstudy-finds-some-significant-differences-brains-men-and-women\"\u003Eoverall overlap in the distributions of men and women&rsquo;s brains is huge\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;So that you get women with big brains and men with small brains.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s worth noting that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3207484\u002F\"\u003EEinstein&rsquo;s brain\u003C\u002Fa\u003E was smaller than that of the average male, and overall, many studies find that there is next to no \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS1041608015300546\"\u003Emean difference between men and women&rsquo;s intelligence\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F25581005\"\u003Ebehavioural traits\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Yet the claims continue to persist in the media.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07pq4zc"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ERippon argues that the apparent structural differences within the brain itself have also been exaggerated. The corpus callosum, for instance, is the bridge of nerve fibres that connects the left and right hemispheres of the brain, with some initial studies finding that this information highway is bigger in women&rsquo;s brain&rsquo;s than in men&rsquo;s brains. This was used to justify all kinds of stereotypes &ndash; like the idea that women are inherently illogical, since their feelings from the &ldquo;emotional&rdquo; right hemisphere were interfering with the processing in the cooler, rational left hemisphere.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs Rippon explains in her book: &ldquo;Men&rsquo;s more efficient callosal filtering mechanism explained the mathematical and scientific genius&hellip; their right to be captains of industry, [their ability to] win Nobel Prizes and so on and so on.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut such claims are often based on just a small number of participants, she says &ndash; and the techniques to measure the &ldquo;size&rdquo; of any region are still rather crude and open to interpretation, meaning that even the existence of such brain differences is on very shaky foundations. (And of course, the idea of the &ldquo;left&rdquo; and &ldquo;right\" brain is itself something of a myth.) Despite decades of research, it has been very difficult to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newscientist.com\u002Farticle\u002Fdn28582-scans-prove-theres-no-such-thing-as-a-male-or-female-brain\u002F\"\u003Ereliably identify significant &ldquo;hardwired&rdquo; differences in the structure of the male and female brain\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaging hormones\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat about our sex hormones? Surely they, at least, should have a very clear impact on our minds and behaviours? Yet the evidence has been misinterpreted to denigrate women&rsquo;s abilities, Rippon says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Women were initially barred from the US space programme, due to concerns of having such &ldquo;temperamental psycho-physiologic humans&rdquo; on board the craft","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe concept of premenstrual syndrome, for instance, first emerged in the 1930s. &ldquo;And it became well established as a reason for women not being given positions of power.&rdquo; As she points out, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.physiology.org\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1152\u002Fadvan.00034.2009?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&amp;rfr_id=ori%3Arid%3Acrossref.org&amp;rfr_dat=cr_pub%3Dpubmed\"\u003Ewomen were even initially barred from the US space programme due to concerns around having such &ldquo;temperamental psycho-physiologic humans&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on board the craft.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile few today would hold this view, we still consider PMS to bring about a range of cognitive and emotional changes that are less than desirable. Yet some of the observed symptoms may be a psychosomatic response &ndash; the result of expectation rather than inevitable biological changes to the brain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn one study by Diane Ruble at Princeton University, for instance, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F560058\"\u003Ewomen were given false feedback about where they were in their menstrual cycle\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;They could give an approximate date about when they expected the period to start &ndash; but you could give them a fake blood test saying, actually, you are now in the pre-menstrual phase, or you're in the intermenstrual phase,&rdquo; Rippon explains. And they were then asked to fill out a questionnaire on various elements of PMS.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07pq55c"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe study found that the women who were told they were in the pre-menstrual phase were much more likely to report the symptoms of PMS &ndash; even if they were not at that stage of the cycle, supporting the idea that some of the symptoms arose from their expectations. (\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20150210-can-you-think-yourself-to-death\"\u003ERead about how the &ldquo;nocebo effect&rdquo; means our beliefs can produce real medical symptoms.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I wouldn't want to underplay the reality of the hormonal changes that are associated with the menstrual cycle, or to deny that people do have changes associated with fluctuations in hormones &ndash; as they should, because the word hormone means stir to action,&rdquo; Rippon says. &ldquo;But if you actually look at things like menstrual diaries, or objective measures of mood changes, the effect is nothing like as profound as the person believes. So the very fact that you believe that [you are] experiencing a mood change, and that must be associated with the premenstrual cycle, becomes a kind of self-fulfilling prophecy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"There are positive cognitive changes about the time of ovulation. Yet I haven't come across an &lsquo;ovulation euphoria questionnaire&rsquo; &ndash; Gina Rippon","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe perceptions of PMS also betray a certain confirmation bias among researchers studying sex and gender differences, who have tended to conduct studies that back up the stereotypes rather than looking for the evidence that may question prevailing assumptions. Rippon says that women may actually experience a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F25222701\"\u003Ecognitive boost at certain points in the menstrual cycle\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, for instance &ndash; but these have been largely ignored, thanks to scientists&rsquo; preoccupation with women&rsquo;s perceived weakness.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We've done some studies showing that cognitively, there are fluctuations through the menstrual cycle,&rdquo; she says. Verbal and spatial working memory, for instance, improve when oestrogen is highest. &ldquo;And that there are very positive changes about the time of ovulation &ndash; improved responsiveness to sensory information, for example, and improved reaction time.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E(\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month\"\u003ERead more about how the menstrual cycle changes women's brains&nbsp;&ndash; for the better\u003C\u002Fa\u003E).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07pq729"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut Rippon says that while the standard tool to measure PMS is the Moos Menstrual Distress Questionnaire, &ldquo;I haven't come across an &lsquo;ovulation \u003Cem\u003Eeuphoria\u003C\u002Fem\u003E questionnaire&rsquo;&rdquo;. The focus, it seems, is always on the negative.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPink and blue tsunamis\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the challenges of studying sex differences has been accounting for the role of culture. Even when apparent differences in the structure of the brain can be observed, there is always the possibility that they arise through nurture rather than nature.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe know that the brain is plastic, meaning it is moulded by experience and training. And as Rippon observed with the birth of her own daughter, a boy and a girl may have very different experiences from the moment they enter the world, as certain behaviours are subtly encouraged. She points to research showing that children as young as 24 months are highly sensitive to gender typical behaviours. They are, she says, &ldquo;tiny social sponges absorbing social information&rdquo;, and adopting those behaviours themselves will eventually rewire their neural circuits. &ldquo;A gendered world produces a gendered brain.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is why the gender stereotyping of toys is such an important issue to address.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;A lot of people think that the idea that we should avoid gendering toys is actually a bit of PC [politically correct] nonsense,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But I think if we take a neuroscientific approach to this, we can see that there's quite profound implications of the toys that we play with when we're very young.&rdquo; These moments of play can be seen as &ldquo;training opportunities&rdquo; that can mould a child&rsquo;s brain into an adult one.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07pq6vk"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EConsider a construction toy like Lego or Duplo or games such as Tetris. As the child plays, rotating bricks and finding increasingly inventive ways to fit them together into new structures, they will be building the neural networks involved in visual and spatial processing. Then, as you get to school, you might perform slightly better at those tasks &ndash; and be praised for your abilities, meaning you&rsquo;ll continue to practice them. Eventually, you may even find a profession that that asks you to spend all day, every day, strengthening those abilities.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Now, if all of those toys and training opportunities are gendered, then you can start getting what looks like a clear gender divide based on the biological sex of an individual, as opposed to the different training opportunities that individual has had,&rdquo; says Rippon.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe psychologists Melissa Terlecki and Nora Newcombe have shown that the apparent \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs11199-005-6765-0\"\u003Esex differences in spatial cognition\u003C\u002Fa\u003E diminish when you account for the amount of time someone has spent playing video games like Tetris, for instance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA few campaigns &ndash; like \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flettoysbetoys.org.uk\u002F\"\u003ELet Toys Be Toys\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the UK and \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.playunlimited.org.au\u002F\"\u003EPlay Unlimited\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in Australia &ndash; have had some success in persuading retailers to change their gendered marketing, but in general, Rippon argues that children are still being pigeonholed in many other ways.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;One of the problems we have in the 21st Century is that what I call gender bombardment is much more intense,&rdquo; says Rippon. &ldquo;There's much more in the social media, and a whole range of marketing initiatives, which make a very clear prescriptive list of what it's like to be male, or what it's like to be female.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07ppz41"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnd this is why Rippon is especially frustrated by the &ldquo;neurosexism&rdquo; out there. The more that tenuous conclusions, from weak data, reach the public, the more likely we are to pass on these messages to children, strengthening those self-fulfilling prophecies.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If we believe that there are profound and fundamental differences between men's and women's brains, and more than that &ndash; that the owners of those brains therefore have access to different skills, or different temperaments or different personalities &ndash; that will certainly affect how we think about ourselves as male or female,&rdquo; says Rippon. &nbsp;It will also affect how we think about other people and what their potential might be, she warns.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;So scientists need to be really careful,&rdquo; she says.&ldquo;Of course, we need to understand where there are sex differences and what they might mean. But we should be careful not to talk about fundamental or profound differences, because we're giving the wrong impression to people who are really interested to know what the answers are to the questions that we're asking.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltimately, we need to accept that each of us has a unique brain &ndash; and our abilities cannot be defined by a single label like our gender.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;An understanding that every brain is different from every other brain, and not necessarily just a function of the sex of the brain&rsquo;s owner, is a really important step forward in the 21st Century,&rdquo; urges Rippon.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E*The video that accompanies this article is part of a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Freel\u002Fplaylist\u002Frethink\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EBBC Reel Playlist called Re:Think\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, where you can watch more thought-provoking films about the human brain.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is a writer based in the London and Barcelona. His first book, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.davidrobson.me\u002F\"\u003EThe Intelligence Trap: Why Smart People Do Dumb Things\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, is out now. He is \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.twitter.com\