ciety responds is having a lasting effect on their health.","summaryShort":"Being a child inside an adult's body can have a lasting impact","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2018-06-11T15:41:14.97477Z","entity":"article","guid":"c5615fd6-5c8f-4577-8f91-23b1c04f6958","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180611-the-health-risks-of-girls-maturing-early","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:28:01.446304Z","project":"future","slug":"20180611-the-health-risks-of-girls-maturing-early","cacheLastUpdated":1587443048835},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india","_id":"5e98209a8ec3f2455a11bb4d","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fhannah-harris-green"],"bodyIntro":"In India, women have died getting sterilised – but it remains the most popular contraceptive method both there, and overall worldwide. Why is it so popular? And what are the drawbacks?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180521-the-health-gap-how-women-experience-the-medical-system\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"http:\u002F\u002Fichef.bbci.co.uk\u002Fimages\u002Fic\u002Fraw\u002Fp067ssc1.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"&ldquo;The\" width=\"100%\" \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERaji Kevat of Ganiyari, Chhattisgarh, has mixed feelings about tubal ligation, the most common form of female sterilisation. It is an operation that she has undergone herself. After she received the procedure in 2014 at one of the Indian government&rsquo;s now-infamous sterilisation &lsquo;camps&rsquo;, she advised her sister-in-law, Shiv Kumari Kevat, to do the same.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShiv Kumari and 82 other women lined up in an otherwise abandoned hospital in the city of Bilaspur in November 2014. The surgeon cut the women \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Findianexpress.com\u002Farticle\u002Findia\u002Findia-others\u002Fbilaspur-8-women-dead-20-others-in-a-serious-condition\u002F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Ewith a single instrument\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E, allegedly without changing his gloves between each surgery. The women were then \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-india-30015755\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Elaid on the hospital floor\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E to recover.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat night, Shiv Kumari began vomiting and experiencing terrible pain in her gut. She was dead within days. While the government&rsquo;s official explanation was that the deaths happened due to compromised drugs, \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fin.reuters.com\u002Farticle\u002Findia-health-sterilisation-chhattisgarh\u002Fpolice-search-chhattisgarh-drug-factory-linked-to-sterilisation-deaths-idINKCN0IY0J620141114\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Ea post-mortem report \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003Eshowed that Shiv Kumari had passed away due to septicaemia &ndash; likely from surgical infection. She was one of 13 women who died from the camp.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwv2"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EStill, says Raji, if anyone asked her, she would advise them to get the procedure, even after losing a family member. Her reason is simple.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If you don&rsquo;t, your family will get too big,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELike many women around the world, Raji considers sterilisation the only real contraceptive option.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like these other stories in the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180521-the-health-gap-how-women-experience-the-medical-system\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EHealth Gap\u003C\u002Fa\u003E:\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180822-the-birth-control-pill-can-have-male-side-effects\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe strange truth about the pill\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180830-what-to-know-about-the-coil-or-iud-contraceptive-method\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe birth control women don&rsquo;t know\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180823-women-speak-about-side-effects-of-the-birth-control-pill\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe dark side of the pill\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"An average of 19% of married or in-union women rely female sterilisation globally","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIf you look at the world as a whole, female sterilisation is the most popular form of contraception. While the pill tends to be more common in Western Europe, Canada or Australia, for example, sterilisation is often the main choice for women elsewhere, including much of Asia and Latin America. \u003Cspan\u003EAccording to a 2015 UN survey,\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E the most recent available, an average of \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.un.org\u002Fen\u002Fdevelopment\u002Fdesa\u002Fpopulation\u002Fpublications\u002Fpdf\u002Ffamily\u002FtrendsContraceptiveUse2015Report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E19% of married or in-union women relied on female sterilisation globally\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E &ndash; the next most popular method, the IUD, is less than 14%, while the pill is just 9%.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd sterilisation is more popular in India than it is anywhere else. In India, the figure for female sterilisation is 39%, almost twice as much as the worldwide number.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESterilised history\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGovernment sterilisation programmes began in the United States. In 1907, the state of Indiana \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.in.gov\u002Fhistory\u002Fmarkers\u002F524.htm\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Epassed a law \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003Erequiring institutionalised persons to be sterilised &ndash; the world&rsquo;s first eugenics law.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwvz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Nazis would later use California&rsquo;s racist eugenics programme as precedent for sterilising Jewish people","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMany other US states passed similar laws. \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fbooks.google.co.in\u002Fbooks?id=1lvbUy441m0C&amp;pg=PA18&amp;redir_esc=y#v=onepage&amp;q=california&amp;f=false\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ENazis would later use \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003ECalifornia&rsquo;s \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.latimes.com\u002Flocal\u002Flanow\u002Fla-me-sterilization-20161226-story.html\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Eracist eugenics program\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.latimes.com\u002Flocal\u002Flanow\u002Fla-me-sterilization-20161226-story.html\"\u003Eme\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E as precedent for sterilising Jewish people. Eugenics laws in the US would mostly be overturned by the 1970s, but they overlapped with the rise of the pill, feminism and the sexual revolution. And it was during this time that governments of recently colonised countries, including the Philippines and Bangladesh as well as India, would also begin to sterilise their populations, with international support. \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fglobal-development\u002F2014\u002Fmar\u002F14\u002Fperu-women-forced-sterilisation-justice\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EPeru\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003C\u002Fspan\u003Eand \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww-jstor-org.proxy.artic.edu\u002Fstable\u002F1973372?Search=yes&amp;resultItemClick=true&amp;searchText=unfpa&amp;searchText=china&amp;searchText=sterilization&amp;searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3Dunfpa%2Bchina%2Bsterilization&amp;refreqid=search%3A62d532cb1c609cf33f907e69b4b528df\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EChina\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E also received foreign aid for their sterilisation programmes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut today, India is the country where the most sterilisations are performed in the world, in terms of both absolute numbers and percentage of the population.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese high numbers might be partially explained by India&rsquo;s history as the world&rsquo;s first country to have a department devoted to family planning, which emphasised sterilisation early on. The Indian government began aggressively promoting sterilisation in the 1970s, and a number of international organisations and governments were happy to provide support, including the World Bank, the US government and the Ford Foundation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwyb"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newspapers.com\u002Fimage\u002F?spot=6966289&amp;fcfToken=6542434167346c6b3139747633326e4750493466727750516c324739456479537547646468596d736c686673694e4572473231344f48625652745036764f66355538454d316235664d4a773d\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EIn a 1977 interview \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003Ewith the St Louis Dispatch, RT Ravenholt, director of the US Office of Population, said that the government&rsquo;s goal was to sterilise a quarter of the world&rsquo;s fertile women &ndash; around 100 million. His argument was that since US medical advances were responsible for the expansion of the world&rsquo;s population, they should also be responsible for keeping it down&hellip; albeit through women&rsquo;s bodies, rather than men&rsquo;s.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EToday, USAID, the arm of the US government that provides funding for family planning services around the world, continues to support some of this thinking: a USAID-funded white paper in 2014 \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.respond-project.org\u002Fpages\u002Ffiles\u002F6_pubs\u002Fadvocacy-materials\u002FCase-for-Perm-Methods-White-Paper-2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Erecommended that sterilisation increase globally\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter a \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-india-30040790\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Eforcible male sterilisation campaign\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E when more than six million low-income men were sterilised and 2,000 died, the Indian government began to change its official approach to family planning.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndian officials moved away from setting &lsquo;targets&rsquo; for the number of people who ought to be sterilised and began investing more in reversible methods of contraception, like the pill. Over the last two years the Indian government rolled out \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com\u002Fcity\u002Fagra\u002Fsecond-phase-of-mission-parivar-vikas-launched-in-40-districts-of-up\u002Farticleshow\u002F62936776.cms\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EMission Parivar Vikas\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E, which offers three new hormonal methods of contraception, including progestin-only contraceptive pills.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Sterilisation isn&rsquo;t only popular in India &ndash; it&rsquo;s on the rise","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"calloutBodyHtml":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the UN, a surprising 22% of US women of child-bearing age who practise contraception have chosen sterilisation, compared with only 16% on the pill. This popularity differs from most developed countries, particularly those in Europe and Oceania.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHealth insurance may explain the US anomaly as policies have not always covered contraceptives, and lifelong s\u003Cspan\u003Eterilisation is cheaper than regular prescriptions\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E. In the past, US state governments also have used sterilisation as a way to control the fertility of women living below the poverty line, as well as black and Hispanic women, who \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.kff.org\u002Fdisparities-policy\u002Fissue-brief\u002Fhealth-coverage-by-race-and-ethnicity-the-potential-impact-of-the-affordable-care-act\u002F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Ehave historically less access to US healthcare coverage\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, between\u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F29038071\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E 2008 and 2014\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E, women across income levels began to rely more on long-acting reversible contraceptives (LARCs) such as the IUD.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","calloutSubtitle":"Why is it is more popular than the pill?","calloutTitle":"Sterilisation in the US","cardType":"CalloutBox","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEven so, sterilisation isn&rsquo;t only popular in India &ndash; it&rsquo;s on the rise. According to UN Statistics, globally the proportion of married or in-union women who have been sterilised has decreased from\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.un.org\u002Fesa\u002Fpopulation\u002Fpublications\u002Fcontraceptive2005\u002F2005_World_Contraceptive_files\u002FWallChart_WCU2005.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E 20.5%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.un.org\u002Fen\u002Fdevelopment\u002Fdesa\u002Fpopulation\u002Fpublications\u002Fpdf\u002Ffamily\u002FtrendsContraceptiveUse2015Report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E19%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E over a decade &ndash; but in India it has risen from 34% to 39%. Government sterilisation camps, meanwhile, continued until 2016.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgvvm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe irreversibility of sterilisation also means that one cannot fairly compare its popularity with that of other methods. Most studies, including the UN survey, count how many women are currently using a type of contraception. While women can, and do, choose to discontinue other methods at any time, once their contraceptive method is sterilisation, that rarely changes: tubal ligation reversal is both costly and likely to fail.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStill, that makes the difference between the numbers of sterilised women globally, versus in India, all the more marked.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermanent fix\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor women around the world who know they don&rsquo;t want children or for mothers who have reached their desired number of children, sterilisation is often a safe and effective option. In the US, for example,\u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjezebel.com\u002F5835015\u002Fwhy-do-so-many-new-mothers-choose-sterilization\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E many new mothers opt for sterilisation right after childbirth,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E and other women will switch from spacing methods (like condoms or the pill) to sterilisation once they&rsquo;ve completed their family.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe upside is that these women never have to think about contraceptive methods again. They&rsquo;re also unlikely to have side effects once they&rsquo;ve recovered from the procedure.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut sometimes, as in Chhattisgarh, women received the sterilisation procedure without fully understanding its significance &ndash; and in unsafe conditions. What happened in Bilaspur &ldquo;was a tragedy waiting to happen&rdquo;, says Yogesh Jain, director of Jan Swasthya Sahyog hospital in Ganiyari, near Shiv Kumari&rsquo;s home. He considers the deaths an inevitable result of policy choices that devalue poor women. &ldquo;I could have written about this 10 years ago that something's going to happen,&rdquo; he says, adding that the women were treated as no more valuable than &ldquo;a uterus and a pair of hands&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwqh"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpopulationfoundation.in\u002Ffiles\u002Ffileattached\u002FFileattached-1480404258-Report-on-Bilaspur-Visit-2-december-2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Ean investigation of the sterilisation camp deaths\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E in Chhattisgarh, the Population Foundation of India (PFI) found that the state government spent about 20 times the amount incentivising women to get the procedure as they spent on the procedure itself &ndash; and women were only paid between 600 and 1400 rupees each (&pound;7-15) to get sterilised. But because of the 2014 tragedy, the national government &ldquo;did wake up to the fact that there is abysmal quality of care in these facilities&rdquo;, says PFI director of programmes Sonal Sharma. She says the Indian government accepted PFI&rsquo;s recommendation that the &lsquo;camp&rsquo; approach to sterilisation be banned.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe government has shifted the focus instead to &lsquo;fixed day&rsquo; services, meaning that women must come to particular facilities on particular days of the week if they want to be sterilised &ndash; which allows better monitoring and regulation of operating room conditions. But in some places, the more limited hours are proving inadequate to service demand for the procedure. At the Mungeli district level hospital about 50km from Bilaspur, for example, a surgeon now comes in to do the procedure two days each week. But that only adds up to about 20 surgeries &ndash; which, says the district&rsquo;s chief medical officer Mukhya Chikitsa, isn&rsquo;t enough for all the women who want it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf sterilisation remains in such high demand even among women in Chhattisgarh despite its now-tainted history there, many women must still see it as their best option.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the procedure remains controversial &ndash; and not only because of preventable deaths like those in Bilaspur.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImperfect answer\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven when performed correctly and in hygienic circumstances, tubal ligation remains more risky \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fqz.com\u002F296019\u002Fvasectomies-are-cheaper-and-safer-than-female-sterilization-so-why-dont-more-men-get-them\u002F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Eand invasive than vasectomy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E. Even so, in the majority of countries, female sterilisation is more popular than male sterilisation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwl9"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe nature of tubal ligation also gives rise to ethical concerns: compared with other types of contraceptives, it is easier to implement without a woman&rsquo;s full consent or understanding. A woman must follow instructions to use methods like the condom or the pill. But once a woman is sterilised, her participation in controlling her fertility is over. Governments have abused this. In Peru in the late 1990s, for example, public medics would \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fglobal-development\u002F2014\u002Fmar\u002F14\u002Fperu-women-forced-sterilisation-justice\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Esterilise poor women without telling them\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E, instead claiming to be performing a different procedure like injecting vitamins intravenously.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Most women who get sterilised in India never use another contraceptive method first to help space out pregnancies, which comes with significant health risks","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne other difficulty is that the emphasis on, and popularity of, sterilisation can encourage women not to use other methods. Most women who get sterilised in India use only this contraceptive method in their lifetime. In other words, they never use something like an intrauterine device (IUD), patch or pill first to help space out pregnancies. This comes with significant health risks: not spacing out pregnancies means that \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4174138\u002F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Eboth the women \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003Eand \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.unicef.org\u002Fabout\u002Fhistory\u002Ffiles\u002Fsourcebook_children_1990s_part3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Etheir children face\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E an increased risk of death and other complications.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis goes hand in hand with the fact that other contraceptive methods, like the pill or IUD, are less available in the country, as are trained professionals who can insert IUDs. And across social classes, women tend to lack knowledge about other methods.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-20"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06kgwmx"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180906-why-female-sterilisation-is-so-popular-in-india-21"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMadhu Goel is a gynaecologist at Fortis La Femme, a high-end private hospital for women in Delhi&rsquo;s Greater Kailash neighbourhood. Even among her patients, sterilisation is still &ldquo;the method&rdquo; of contraception, she says. Though that&rsquo;s especially true of older women, younger patients also have misgivings about alternatives. Even most young women who spoke with her after researching contraception on the internet had misconceptions about the pill &ndash; believing that it causes permanent infertility, for example.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut Goel says that, at least among her patients, social change in India means that more women are educating themselves about other options. Divorce rates in India are going up, for example. As a result more women want to reverse their sterilisations, hoping to start new families with their second husbands.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolicy may eventually have an effect, too. The \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwcd.nic.in\u002Fsites\u002Fdefault\u002Ffiles\u002Fwomen%20empowerment%20poliy_Final_17May.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ENational Policy for Women\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E laid out by the ministry of Women and Child Development in 2016 outlines a shift focus from female to male sterilisation. But according to experts, this policy has yet to be put into practice.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the international machine that has made female sterilisation so popular in India, it might take time to make a real dent in its dominance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis story was reported with support by the Pulitzer Center for Crisis Reporting.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis story is part of the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fbbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180521-the-health-gap-how-women-experience-the-medical-system\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EHealth Gap\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E a special series about how men and women experience the medical system &ndash; and their own health &ndash; in starkly different ways.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDo you have an experience to share? Or are you just interested in sharing information about women's health and wellbeing? Join our Facebook group\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fbbc.in\u002F2LQHVAC\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EFuture Woman\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Eand be a part of the conversation about the day-to-day issues that affect women&rsquo;s lives.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 800,000+ Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\