ias-affects-your-healthcare"],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Many countries turn a blind eye to domestic abuse – but Nepal's approach could be the model for a global solution.","summaryShort":"It causes 2 million injuries a year in the US alone","tag":["tag\u002Fhealth","tag\u002Fgender"],"creationDateTime":"2018-10-24T23:40:40.379835Z","entity":"article","guid":"40643447-90c0-4ee5-92a1-1dee3b4920bc","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181023-nepals-plans-to-save-womens-lives","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:28:01.446304Z","project":"future","slug":"20181023-nepals-plans-to-save-womens-lives","cacheLastUpdated":1587443048834},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science","_id":"5e98209c8ec3f2455a11c25a","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fmary-k-feeney"],"bodyIntro":"More women are graduating with PhDs in science – so why was Donna Strickland only the third female physicist to receive a Nobel prize?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne of the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nobelprize.org\u002Fprizes\u002Fphysics\u002F2018\u002Fstrickland\u002Ffacts\u002F\"\u003E2018 Nobel prizes in physics\u003C\u002Fa\u003E went to Donna Strickland, a major accomplishment for any scientist. Yet much of the news coverage has focused on the fact that she&rsquo;s only the third female physicist to receive the award, after \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nobelprize.org\u002Fprizes\u002Fphysics\u002F1903\u002Fmarie-curie\u002Ffacts\u002F\"\u003EMarie Curie in 1903\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nobelprize.org\u002Fprizes\u002Fphysics\u002F1963\u002Fmayer\u002Ffacts\u002F\"\u003EMaria Goeppert-Mayer\u003C\u002Fa\u003E 60 years later.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough biochemical engineer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nobelprize.org\u002Fprizes\u002Fchemistry\u002F2018\u002Farnold\u002Ffacts\u002F\"\u003EFrances Arnold\u003C\u002Fa\u003E also won this year, for chemistry, the rarity of female Nobel laureates raises questions about women&rsquo;s exclusion from education and careers in science. Female researchers have come a long way over the past century. But there&rsquo;s overwhelming evidence that women remain underrepresented in the Stem fields of science, technology, engineering and math.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStudies have shown those who persist in these careers face explicit and implicit barriers to advancement. Bias is most intense in fields that are predominantly male, where women lack a critical mass of representation and are often viewed as tokens or outsiders.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20171010-how-many-female-scientists-can-you-name\"\u003EHow many female scientists can you name?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180531-how-womens-body-parts-have-been-named-after-men\"\u003EThe case for renaming women&rsquo;s body parts\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20121008-winning-formula-for-nobel-prizes\"\u003ENobel prizes: Is there a secret formula to winning one? \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen women achieve at the highest levels of sports, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fj.1468-2508.2006.00402.x\"\u003Epolitics\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC1002790\u002F\"\u003Emedicine\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and science, they \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1080\u002F1047840X.2011.607313\"\u003Eserve as role models\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for all of us, especially for girls and other women. But are things getting better in terms of equal representation? And what still holds women back in the classroom, in the lab, in leadership and as award winners?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecious stereotypes\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETraditional stereotypes hold that women &lsquo;don&rsquo;t like math&rsquo; and &lsquo;aren&rsquo;t good at science&rsquo;. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencemag.org\u002Fnews\u002F2014\u002F03\u002Fboth-genders-think-women-are-bad-basic-math\"\u003EBoth men and women report these viewpoints\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; but \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.apa.org\u002Faction\u002Fresources\u002Fresearch-in-action\u002Fshare.aspx\"\u003Eresearchers have empirically disputed them\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Studies show that girls and women avoid Stem education not because of cognitive inability, but because of early exposure and experience with Stem, educational policy, cultural context, stereotypes and a lack of exposure to role models.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06n8j2t"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFor the past several decades, efforts to improve the representation of women in Stem fields have focused on countering these stereotypes with \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.apsbridgeprogram.org\u002Figen\u002F\"\u003Eeducational reforms\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fgirlswhocode.com\u002F\"\u003Eindividual\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nsf.gov\u002Ffunding\u002Fpgm_summ.jsp?pims_id=5383\"\u003Eprogrammes\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that can increase the number of girls entering and staying in what&rsquo;s been called the Stem pipeline &ndash; the path from primary and secondary school to university to postgraduate training.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Women earn about 18% of PhDs in physics, an increase from 1975 when women earned 5% of PhDs in physics","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThese approaches are working. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1615\u002FJWomenMinorScienEng.2012002908\"\u003EWomen are increasingly likely to express an interest in Stem careers and pursue Stem majors\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in university. Women now make up half or more of workers in psychology and social sciences and are increasingly represented in the scientific workforce, though computer and mathematical sciences are an exception. According to the American Institute of Physics, women earn about 20% of bachelor&rsquo;s degrees and 18% of PhDs in physics, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.aip.org\u002Ftaxonomy\u002Fterm\u002F155\"\u003Ean increase from 1975\u003C\u002Fa\u003E when women earned 10% of bachelor&rsquo;s degrees and 5% of PhDs in physics.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore women are graduating with Stem PhDs and earning faculty positions. But they go on to encounter glass cliffs and ceilings as they advance through their academic careers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStem ceiling\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003EWomen face a number of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1146\u002Fannurev.so.21.080195.000401\"\u003Estructural and institutional barriers\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in academic Stem careers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to issues related to the gender pay gap, the structure of academic science often makes it difficult for women to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.taylorfrancis.com\u002Fbooks\u002F9781135943974\"\u003Eget ahead in the workplace\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and to balance work and life commitments. Bench science can require years of dedicated time in a laboratory. The strictures of the tenure-track process can make maintaining work-life balance, responding to family obligations, and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fwhy-todays-long-stem-postdoc-positions-are-effectively-anti-mother-51550\"\u003Ehaving children\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or taking family leave difficult, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F0306312711417730\"\u003Eif not impossible\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1023\u002FA:1010344929577\"\u003EAdditionally, working in male-dominated workplaces can leave women feeling isolated, perceived as tokens and susceptible to harassment. Women often are excluded from networking opportunities\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and social events and left to feel they&rsquo;re outside the culture of the lab, the academic department and the field.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"When women lack critical mass &ndash; of about 15% or more &ndash; they are less empowered to advocate for themselves and more likely to be perceived as a minority group and an exception","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen women lack critical mass &ndash; of about 15% or more &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.jstor.org\u002Fstable\u002F2884712\"\u003Ethey are less empowered to advocate for themselves\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and more likely to be perceived as a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fj.1749-6632.1999.tb08353.x\"\u003Eminority group and an exception\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. When in this minority position, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1007\u002Fs11162-017-9454-2\"\u003Ewomen are more likely to be pressured to take on extra service\u003C\u002Fa\u003E as &lsquo;tokens&rsquo; on committees or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.chronicle.com\u002Farticle\u002FGhost-Advising\u002F242729\"\u003Eas mentors to female graduate students\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06n8j17"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWith fewer female colleagues, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F0162243917735900\"\u003Ewomen are less likely to build relationships with female collaborators\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1007\u002Fs11192-010-0256-y\"\u003Esupport and advice networks\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. This isolation can be exacerbated when women are unable to participate in work events or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.insidehighered.com\u002Fadvice\u002F2018\u002F02\u002F07\u002Fconferences-should-be-more-family-friendly-women-scholars-children-opinion\"\u003Eattend conferences because of family or child care\u003C\u002Fa\u003E responsibilities and an inability to use research funds to reimburse child care.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUniversities, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.lww.com\u002Facademicmedicine\u002FFulltext\u002F2002\u002F10000\u002FIncreasing_Women_s_Leadership_in_Academic.23.aspx\"\u003Eprofessional associations\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and federal funders have \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1002\u002Fhrm.20225\"\u003Eworked to address a variety of these structural barriers\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Efforts include creating family-friendly policies, increasing transparency in salary reporting, enforcing Title IX protections in the US, providing mentoring and support programmes for women scientists, protecting research time for women scientists, and targeting women for hiring, research support and advancement.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese programmes have mixed results. For example, research indicates that family-friendly policies such as leave and onsite child care \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1093\u002Fscipol\u002Fscu006\"\u003Ecan exacerbate gender inequity\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, resulting in increased research productivity for men and increased teaching and service obligations for women.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of us &ndash; the general public, the media, university employees, students and professors &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fmost-people-think-man-when-they-think-scientist-how-can-we-kill-the-stereotype-42393\"\u003Ehave ideas of what a scientist and a Nobel Prize winner looks like\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fcdev.13039\"\u003EThat image\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fj.1949-8594.2002.tb18217.x\"\u003Epredominantly male, white and older\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; which makes sense given 97% of the science Nobel Prize winners have been men. \u003Cem\u003E(It isn't just science: BBC Future recently created a composite face of all the members of the US Congress. You can see it \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20171018-this-is-the-face-of-the-average-american-politician\"\u003Ehere\u003C\u002Fa\u003E).\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pbs.org\u002Fvideo\u002Fpov-implicit-bias-peanut-butter-jelly-and-racism\u002F\"\u003Eimplicit bias\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: one of the unconscious, involuntary, natural, unavoidable assumptions that all of us, men and women, form about the world around us. People make decisions \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fmeasuring-the-implicit-biases-we-may-not-even-be-aware-we-have-74912\"\u003Ebased on subconscious assumptions, preferences and stereotypes\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; sometimes even when they are counter to their explicitly held beliefs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Women seeking academic jobs are more likely to be viewed and judged based on personal information and physical appearance","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch shows that an implicit bias against women as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.scientificamerican.com\u002Farticle\u002Fwhat-a-scientist-looks-like\u002F\"\u003Eexperts and academic scientists is pervasive\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It manifests itself by valuing, acknowledging and rewarding men&rsquo;s scholarship over women&rsquo;s scholarship. Implicit bias can work against women&rsquo;s hiring, advancement and recognition of their work. For instance, women seeking academic jobs are more likely to be viewed and judged based on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.aeaweb.org\u002Fconference\u002F2018\u002Fpreliminary\u002Fpaper\u002FnZ24K7b2\"\u003Epersonal information and physical appearance\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Letters of recommendation for women are \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1007\u002Fs10869-018-9541-1\"\u003Emore likely to raise doubts\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and use language that results in negative career outcomes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImplicit bias can affect women&rsquo;s ability to publish research findings and gain recognition for that work. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F2378023117738903\"\u003EMen cite their own papers 56% more than women do\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Known as the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F0306312711435830\"\u003E&ldquo;Matilda Effect&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, there is a gender gap in recognition, award winning and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.insidehighered.com\u002Fnews\u002F2018\u002F08\u002F16\u002Fnew-research-shows-extent-gender-gap-citations\"\u003Ecitations\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Women&rsquo;s research is less likely to be cited by others and their \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.7910\u002FDVN\u002FR7AQT1\"\u003Eideas are more likely to be attributed to men\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.insidehighered.com\u002Fnews\u002F2017\u002F04\u002F20\u002Fstudy-finds-women-economics-write-papers-are-more-readable-face-longer-publication\"\u003EWomen&rsquo;s solo-authored research takes twice as long\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to move through the review process. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1038\u002Fd41586-018-06678-6\"\u003EWomen are underrepresented\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fpuar.12950\"\u003Ejournal editorships\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, as senior scholars and lead authors, and as peer reviewers. This marginalisation in research gatekeeping positions works against the promotion of women&rsquo;s research.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen a woman becomes a world-class scientist, implicit bias works \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1128\u002FJVI.00739-17\"\u003Eagainst the likelihood\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that she will be \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theatlantic.com\u002Fscience\u002Farchive\u002F2017\u002F12\u002Fwomen-are-invited-to-give-fewer-talks-than-men-at-top-us-universities\u002F548657\u002F\"\u003Einvited as a keynote or guest speaker\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to share her research findings, thus \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1111\u002Fjeb.12198\"\u003Elowering her visibility\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the field and the likelihood that she will be \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F0306312711435830\"\u003Enominated for awards\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. This gender imbalance is \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1017\u002FS1049096517000580\"\u003Enotable in how infrequently\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thestar.com\u002Fopinion\u002Fpublic_editor\u002F2017\u002F11\u002F17\u002Fwe-need-more-womens-voices-in-the-news.html\"\u003Ewomen experts\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.poynter.org\u002Fnews\u002Flack-female-sources-ny-times-front-page-stories-highlights-need-change\"\u003Equoted in news stories\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on most topics.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen scientists are afforded less of the respect and recognition that should come with their accomplishments. Research shows that when people talk about male scientists and experts, they&rsquo;re more likely to use their surnames and more likely to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1073\u002Fpnas.1805284115\"\u003Erefer to women by their first names\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Why does this matter? Because experiments show that individuals referred to by their surnames are more likely to be viewed as famous and eminent. In fact, one study found that calling scientists by their last names led people to consider them 14% more deserving of a National Science Foundation career award.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06n8j10"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-why-dont-more-women-dont-win-nobel-prizes-in-science-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EStrickland winning a Nobel Prize as an associate professor in physics is a major accomplishment; doing so as a woman who has almost certainly faced more barriers than her male counterparts is, in my view, monumental.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen asked what it felt like to be the third female Nobel laureate in physics, Strickland noted that at first it was surprising to realise so few women had won the award. &ldquo;But, I mean, I do live in a world of mostly men, so seeing mostly men doesn&rsquo;t really ever surprise me either,&rdquo; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.npr.org\u002F2018\u002F10\u002F02\u002F653779921\u002Fdonna-strickland-becomes-first-woman-in-more-than-50-years-to-win-physics-nobel-\"\u003Eshe said\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeeing mostly men has been the history of science. Addressing structural and implicit bias in Stem will hopefully prevent another half-century wait before the next woman is acknowledged with a Nobel Prize for her contribution to physics. I look forward to the day when a woman receiving the most prestigious award in science is newsworthy only for her science and not her gender.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis article \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fwhy-more-women-dont-win-science-nobels-104370\"\u003Eoriginally appeared\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Eon The Conversation, and is republished under a Creative Commons licence.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 900,000+ Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u0