:{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EInstead of rogue wombs, the main source of these changes is the ovaries, which release oestrogen and progesterone in different quantities throughout the month. The hormones are primarily tasked with thickening the lining of the womb and deciding when to release an egg. They also have profound effects on women&rsquo;s brains and behaviour.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScientists have been studying the menstrual cycle since the 1930s. It&rsquo;s a surprisingly popular research topic, and we now know that it has all kinds of quirky effects, from influencing a woman&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.liebertpub.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1089\u002Fjwh.2007.0423\"\u003Eability to give up smoking\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.tandfonline.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1076\u002Fbrhm.34.3.295.18808\"\u003Etypes of dreams she has each night\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut this mountain of knowledge wasn&rsquo;t born out of a fascination with female biology. Instead, it was driven by a desire to understand the ways in which men and women are different &ndash; and why.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne example of this difference is in our brains. The physical differences between the sexes extend to these wrinkly organs, and scientists have suspected for years that they are down to hormones. &ldquo;Basically we jump on these natural fluctuations in sex hormone levels that we find,&rdquo; says Markus Hausmann, a neuroscientist at the University of Durham. &ldquo;This might be the menstrual cycle in women, or seasonal fluctuations in testosterone levels in men. It&rsquo;s a full natural experiment.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Women speak sooner than men, they&rsquo;re more verbally fluent than men, and they&rsquo;re actually better at spelling than men &ndash; Pauline Maki","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne way women are different is that they have superior social skills. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fprofile\u002FSimon_Baron-Cohen\u002Fpublication\u002F232430614_The_Essential_Difference_The_Truth_About_The_Male_And_Female_Brain\u002Flinks\u002F547cdb7a0cf2cfe203c1fde2\u002FThe-Essential-Difference-The-Truth-About-The-Male-And-Female-Brain.pdf\"\u003EWomen have better empathy and theory of mind\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; the understanding that other humans may have a perspective different to our own. They also have better communication skills. This is thought to be part of the reason that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3945617\u002F\"\u003Emale children are four times more likely to be diagnosed with high-functioning autism\u003C\u002Fa\u003E; girls are better at disguising their symptoms.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Women speak sooner than men, they&rsquo;re more verbally fluent than men, and they&rsquo;re actually better at spelling than men,&rdquo; says Pauline Maki, a psychologist at the University of Illinois, Chicago.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThis social advantage is thought to have evolved because, thousands of years ago, articulate mothers would have been better at conveying vital information to their children &ndash; such as not to eat certain poisonous plants.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut are hormones involved? And if so, how much?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormonal balance\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003EBack in 2002, together with colleagues from the Gerontology Research Center in Baltimore, Maki set out to learn \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F11749982\"\u003Ehow fluctuating oestrogen levels affect women&rsquo;s abilities over the course of each month\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Each participant was assessed twice: once just after their period, when oestrogen and progesterone levels were low, and once about a week after they ovulated, when oestrogen and progesterone were high.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt was a small study, involving 16 women who were asked to complete a range of mental tests. But the findings were notable.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring days when the participants had more female hormones in their systems, they were significantly worse at the things men are usually good at (like spatial awareness) and much better at the things women tend to have an edge in (such as the ability to come up with new words). When their hormone levels were lower, their spatial awareness was restored.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne ability that improved when female hormones was higher was &lsquo;implicit remembering&rsquo;, which Maki describes as the subconscious, effortless kind of memory. &ldquo;If I said to you, &lsquo;Oh, what was the last Uber fare you had &ndash; was it more or less than the Lyft fare?&rsquo; And then later on, I asked you, &lsquo;How do you spell fare?&rsquo;. You might spell it f-a-r-e, even though most people spell it f-a-i-r. Because somewhere your brain encoded &lsquo;fare&rsquo; and that was heightened.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese implicit word memories are important for developing communication skills. They&rsquo;re the reason we often find ourselves using obscure words or turns of phrase, like &ldquo;Oh, he was so obstinate&rdquo;, just after hearing someone else use them, or reading them in an article.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a result, Maki believes these monthly changes were primarily driven by oestrogen.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hormone affects two neighbouring brain regions. The first is the seahorse-shaped hippocampus, which is involved in storing memories. Evidence is mounting that the hippocampus is vital to social abilities, since being able to remember your own experiences can help you to understand the motivations of others. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1002\u002Fhipo.20468\"\u003EThe region gets bigger each month\u003C\u002Fa\u003E when more female hormones are floating around.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second is the amygdala, which helps us to process emotions, especially fear and the decision to fight or flee. Intriguingly, the amygdala also may be crucial to avoiding social blunders, because understanding why a person is fearful &ndash; and deciding if we should be too &ndash; requires us to see the world from their perspective. Once you have this ability, you can use it to your advantage in other ways, such as to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4834434\u002F\"\u003Emake moral judgements\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or even \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.psychologytoday.com\u002Fus\u002Fblog\u002Fulterior-motives\u002F201512\u002Fwhen-children-learn-about-others-minds-they-learn-lie\"\u003Etell lies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Women who lack the ability to produce oestrogen aren&rsquo;t as good at recognising fear and tend to have poor social skills","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs it happens, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpsych.cf.ac.uk\u002Fhome2\u002Flewis\u002F26%20Pearson%20Lewis%20Fear%20Hormones%20and%20Behavior%202005.pdf\"\u003Ewomen&rsquo;s abilities to recognise fear peak with their oestrogen levels\u003C\u002Fa\u003E each month. If the hormone is responsible, it also might help explain why women tend to have better social skills overall. The idea is backed up by the fact that women who lack the ability to produce oestrogen \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F12597072\"\u003Earen&rsquo;t as good at recognising fear\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and tend to have \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.tandfonline.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1080\u002F13554799908402746?journalCode=nncs20\"\u003Epoor social skills\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaki believes that most of the effects our menstrual cycles have on our minds are sheer accident. For years, researchers thought that some monthly changes had an evolutionary advantage, such as the widely-reported discoveries that women prefer more masculine, symmetrical men when they&rsquo;re at their most fertile. But this isn&rsquo;t actually true &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fjournals.sagepub.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1177\u002F1754073914523073\"\u003Eseveral large-scale studies haven&rsquo;t found any link\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain power\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut regardless of why it exists, the monthly transformation of women&rsquo;s brains could still be an advantage.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reason lies in another major difference between male and female brains. The latter tend to be less &lsquo;lateralised&rsquo; &ndash; rather than using just one side of the brain to complete a task, like solve a maths problem, women are more likely to use both.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese left-right divisions are relatively stable. &ldquo;Most people show a lateralised effect when it comes to the hands,&rdquo; says Hausmann. &ldquo;So for example, I&rsquo;m right-handed. This tells us something about where language is located in my brain. More right-handers have language localised in the left side of the brain than left-handers.&rdquo; This specialisation is thought to be useful, since most species &ndash; from lungfish to lizards &ndash; have brains built this way.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180806-how-the-menstrual-cycle-changes-womens-brains-every-month-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhy women&rsquo;s brains are less so is a big mystery. But this fluctuates, too. Back in 2002, Hausmann discovered that &ndash; as with other &lsquo;female&rsquo; traits &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F11900731\"\u003Ea woman&rsquo;s tendency to use both sides becomes more extreme\u003C\u002Fa\u003E when oestrogen and progesterone levels increase each month. One possible advantage is that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1002\u002Fjnr.23857\"\u003Ethese shifts allow for more flexibility in thinking\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;When people have a different pattern in their brains over the course of the month, with them becoming more or less lateralised, this could lead to different strategies of how to solve a particular problem,&rdquo; says Hausmann. &ldquo;So people who rely more on the left hemisphere may solve problems in a more logical way, and people who rely more on the right hemisphere maybe rely more on holistic processes when they try to solve a task.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next time someone asks if you&rsquo;re hormonal, you can say yes &ndash; but it isn&rsquo;t necessarily a bad thing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis story is part of the \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180521-the-health-gap-how-women-experience-the-medical-system\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHealth Gap\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, a special series about how men and women experience the medical system &ndash; and their own health &ndash; in starkly different ways.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDo you have an experi